Comment:
[{'comment': 'We can use try-with-resources now.
I know this is only a refactoring but we can take this opportunity to clean up code', 'commenter': 'eolivelli'}, {'comment': 'The propagation of `IOException`s on `close()` is prevented (only logging is done), in contrast to other `IOException`s. I guess we need to keep this behaviour, right?
If so, try-with-resources doesn't appear beneficial to me. For instance, this might be the code:
```java
try (InputStream inputStream = new FileInputStream(new File(trustStorePath))) {
    ts.load(inputStream, passwordStringToCharArray(trustStorePassword));
    return ts;
} catch (IOException e) {
    // some cumbersome logic to differentiate IOExceptions
    boolean isExceptionOnClose = ...;
    if (isExceptionOnClose) {
        LOG.info("Failed to close key store input stream", e);
    } else {
        throw e;
    }
}
```
Or I'm missing something?', 'commenter': 'ivanyu'}, {'comment': "@ivanyu I see your point and I thought about it before adding this comment, thank you for pointing it out explicitly.
An exception on close() is really unexpected and it is a symptom of a weird status of the system  (and we can end with open FD leaks...)

So I don't see much value in keeping the method exiting normally when there is something bad going on.

As a counterpart the try-with-resources is a cleaner syntax.

It is just nitpicking, it is not a blocker for this change to be merged.

How does it sound to you ?", 'commenter': 'eolivelli'}, {'comment': "I totally share this idea about making the methods fail explicitly if closing fails. So I've changed to try-with-resources.", 'commenter': 'ivanyu'}]

